      Form PF
   =20
 =20
If you run a hedge fund, and you lose 30% of your fund=E2=80=99s value in a=
 day, I guess you have to tell someone? That seems unpleasant. I mean, in t=
he first instance, your prime broker probably already knows about it: They =
were keeping track of your stuff anyway, and probably lending you money aga=
inst it, and now they know that it has gone down and are probably calling=
=C2=A0you=C2=A0to say things like =E2=80=9Chey man you okay?=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cwe are going to need a lot more margin from you by the end of the =
day.=E2=80=9DBut also high on your list of concerns will be your clients, t=
he people whose money you just lost. Sure you send them a quarterly investo=
r letter full of classical quotes to explain your performance, but if you d=
rop 30% in a day that news probably can=E2=80=99t wait until the end of the=
 quarter and a perfectly chosen aphorism from Marcus Aurelius. You=E2=80=99=
re gonna want to pick up the phone.Now I guess you will also have to tell t=
he SEC about it:Federal regulators proposed measures that would significant=
ly increase their visibility into private-equity funds and some hedge funds=
, the first in a range of plans to expand oversight of private markets.The =
Securities and Exchange Commission voted 3-1 to issue a proposal that would=
 increase the amount and timeliness of confidential information that privat=
e-equity and hedge funds report to the agency on a document known as Form P=
F.The main goal, Chairman Gary Gensler said, is to allow regulators to bett=
er spot risks building up in private markets, stepping up an effort that be=
gan after the 2008 financial crisis. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Among other changes, We=
dnesday=E2=80=99s proposal would require large hedge funds to file reports =
within one business day of incidents such as extraordinary investment losse=
s, large increases in margin requirements or defaults by major counterparti=
es.Here are the SEC=E2=80=99s press release, fact sheet and proposed rule. =
Some of the things that hedge funds would have to report promptly include =
=E2=80=9Ca loss equal to or greater than 20 percent of a fund=E2=80=99s mos=
t recent net asset value over a rolling 10 business day period,=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=9Ca cumulative increase in margin of more than 20 percent of the rep=
orting fund=E2=80=99s most recent net asset value over a rolling 10 busines=
s day period,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ca fund=E2=80=99s margin default or inabilit=
y to meet a call for margin, collateral, or an equivalent,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=9Ca margin default by a counterparty,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Crequests for r=
edemption exceeding 50 percent of the most recent net asset value.=E2=80=9D=
 If your fund experiences bad stuff that might suggest a serious problem, y=
ou=E2=80=99ll have to tell the SEC.What will they do about it? I don=E2=80=
=99t know. Whenever there is=C2=A0big sudden weird market turbulence =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0 Archegos,  GameStop =E2=80=94=C2=A0I read complaints that the SEC=
 needs to get more detailed real-time information so it can head off that t=
urbulence, but I feel like I never hear about cases where the SEC=C2=A0did=
=C2=A0use its detailed real-time information to head off turbulence? Perhap=
s that is a structural feature of turbulence =E2=80=94=C2=A0you don=E2=80=
=99t hear about it when it doesn=E2=80=99t happen =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the SE=
C is in fact often calling up investment managers to say =E2=80=9Chey you o=
wn too much of this one stock and it=E2=80=99s about to go down, you should=
 sell some, but carefully.=E2=80=9D I just don=E2=80=99t really see how tha=
t would work. But this is from the SEC release proposing the new rules:In o=
ur experience, losses of 20 percent or more of a fund=E2=80=99s most recent=
 net asset value during this period could indicate significant stress at th=
e fund or the markets in which the fund participates that could raise inves=
tor protection and systemic risk concerns warranting prompt reporting. For =
example, these losses could signal a precipitous liquidation or broader mar=
ket=C2=A0instability that could lead to secondary effects, including greate=
r margin and collateral requirements, financing costs for the fund, and the=
 potential for large investor redemptions. Notice of large losses could pro=
vide notice to the Commission and FSOC of potential fund or market issues i=
n advance of the occurrence of more downstream consequences, such as sharp =
margin increases, defaults, or fund liquidation. Also, funds in serious str=
ess may be in the process of deleveraging, exiting certain strategies, or l=
iquidating securities in a declining market with implications for both fund=
 investors and systemic risk. Moreover, large, sharp, and sustained losses =
suffered by one fund within this short period may signal concern for simila=
rly situated funds, allowing the Commission and FSOC to analyze the scale a=
nd scope of the event and whether additional funds that may have similar in=
vestments, market positions, or financing profiles are at risk.What do they=
 do with that analysis? Is it, like, like, Hedge Fund X loses 30% of its va=
lue and gets a lot of margin calls, and it tells the SEC, and the SEC analy=
zes its holdings, and then the SEC calls up other funds with similar holdin=
gs and says =E2=80=9Chey just FYI there are some big liquidations coming, y=
ou might want to get out of those stocks=E2=80=9D? Or does it call the othe=
r funds and say =E2=80=9Chey just FYI we=E2=80=99d consider it a personal f=
avor if you don=E2=80=99t sell those stocks and maybe buy a bit more=E2=80=
=9D? I am not sure how the SEC=E2=80=99s real-time systemic-risk management=
 is supposed to work, but I guess it could always use more information.
