cement mechanisms, etc.; I feel like you would have a tough time meeting th=
e definition of =E2=80=9Ccode of ethics=E2=80=9D with a short statement.[3]=
 See NYSE Listed Company Manual Section 303A.10 and Nasdaq Rule 5610.[4] To=
 become a lawyer, in the U.S., you need to pass an ethics test called the M=
ultistate Professional Responsibility Examination. The MPRE is a multiple-c=
hoice test, and prospective lawyers generally take a prep class for it, and=
 the famous advice in this class is that you should choose the second-most =
ethical answer to each question. You=E2=80=99re supposed to be, you know, m=
edium-ethical.[5] Let me revise that. =E2=80=9CPossibly due to the moral pr=
eferences of their boards and CEOs, but I=E2=80=99m  not a big believer tha=
t the moral preferences of boards and CEOs are all that interesting as an a=
nalytical lens for corporate decisions.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 Also I think that in=
 *talking about* these things boards and CEOs often prefer to speak in the =
language of =E2=80=9Clong-term value=E2=80=9D or shareholder preferences ra=
ther than the language of =E2=80=9CI think that this is the moral thing to =
do,=E2=80=9D because they have been acculturated into a world in which thei=
r main responsibility is to shareholders rather than to their personal sens=
e of morality.[6] There is a third, bureaucratic answer: Companies are lega=
lly required to have someone write a code of ethics, so an industry of writ=
ing codes of ethics sprung up, and the people in that industry are always l=
ooking to expand their responsibilities. I assume there is a fair amount of=
 truth to that one.
