harassment of any kind and we hold everyone accountable immediately,=E2=80=
=9D then it will be easier for shareholders to argue that they were deceive=
d.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The last few years in the financia=
l markets have involved (1) a huge growth in the size and salience of ESG i=
nvesting and (2) a huge growth in the volume and creativity of everything-i=
s-securities-fraud lawsuits, which kind of cut in opposite directions. You =
could imagine companies=C2=A0<em>paring down=C2=A0</em>their codes of ethic=
s to avoid getting sued all the time, or=C2=A0<em>beefing up=C2=A0</em>thei=
r codes to seek favor with ESG investors.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">But there is an actual answer, which is =E2=80=9Cbeefing up=E2=80=9D:<=
/p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the past decade, corporate=
 scandals have proliferated. These scandals, along with the emergence of th=
e #MeToo movement and Environmental, Social, and Corporate Governance (ESG)=
 mandates, have increased the scrutiny of corporations=E2=80=99 ethics cult=
ure. How have companies responded in terms of the language appearing in the=
ir public ethics documents? We compare the Code of Ethics in 2008 versus 20=
19 for a sample of S&amp;P 500 firms. For the vast majority of firms, their=
 Code of Ethics lengthened, with the average 2019 code having 29 percent mo=
re words (about 1,760 words) than the 2008 average. The language of the cod=
es has also changed. Words such as bribery, corruption, sustainability, spe=
ak up, bullying, slavery, and human rights all saw significantly higher usa=
ge in the later period. We review possible reasons for the dramatic changes=
, and suggest what questions remain about the motivations behind them. Whet=
her the changes we observe are primarily intrinsically motivated or simply =
market responses to public pressures is yet to be determined. What is clear=
 from our findings is that society seems to be entering a new age of increa=
singly moral=E2=80=94or, at least, moralized=E2=80=94corporate governance.<=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is the abstract to =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26508271.275627=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTM4OD=
c3NDM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB24cbc9d9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">How Have Corporate Codes=
 of Ethics Responded to an Era of Increased Scrutiny?</a>=E2=80=9D by Tim L=
oughran, Bill McDonald and James Otteson. The point I want to make here is =
that beefing up your corporate code of ethics is=C2=A0<em>costly</em>, and =
in some loose sense<em> binding:</em> The more things that are clearly proh=
ibited by your code of ethics, the more likely you are to get sued if someo=
ne does them. If your code of ethics says =E2=80=9Cwe will not use slavery=
=E2=80=9D and you use slavery you will definitely, definitely get sued!=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And companies are incurring these costs=
. Possibly out of, like, intrinsic corporate morality, but I=E2=80=99m not =
a big believer in intrinsic corporate morality.[5] More likely it is becaus=
e shareholders, loosely speaking, demand that they have these policies, and=
 so the companies=C2=A0are doing what shareholders want.[6] And because eve=
rything is securities fraud, if companies don=E2=80=99t follow those codes,=
 the shareholders can sue. In some rough and approximate sense, shareholder=
s have found a binding way to make companies more ethical.</p><table class=
